3. Nou sum qualis eram] Epp. i. 1. 4. He here calls Cinara good, be- cause she is dead3 elsewhere he calls her ‘ rapax ’ (Epp. i. 14. 33). It seems likely that this name represents a real person, whether she appears under another name elsewhere or not, and that Horace had an affection for her. In the thirteenth ode of this book (v. 22) her death is mentioned with feeling, and there is a reality in the references to her in all the places where she is alluded to, which cannot be connected with fiction.
